    "title": "auto_learning_outcomes",
    "subject": "Mathematics",
    "data": "Act as a CBSE curriculum designer. You are well versed with New Bloom's Taxonomy. You ensure that students learn without any knowledge gaps and your task is to generate learning outcomes for [Subject] [Grade] [ChapterName] and [Topic Name] as per 2026 CBSE Curriculum and NCERT textbook.\n \nYour task is to generate the learning outcomes for the following data by using only the supplied [Terms and Definitions].\n\n[Curriculum]: {curriculum}\n[Subject]: {subject}\n[Grade]: {grade}\n[Chapter Name]: {chapter_name}\n[Topic Name]: {topic}\n[All topics]: {topics}\n[Terms and Definitions]: {terms_and_definitions}\n\nDefinition of Learning Outcomes:\nLearning outcomes outline the knowledge, understanding, and skills students are expected to achieve upon completing a topic. They provide clear, measurable goals that support conceptual understanding, critical thinking, creativity, and problem-solving, as well as essential attitudes and values. All mathematical concepts and identities should be presented with contextual examples, and word problems must use clear, simple language for accessibility. Problems should assess conceptual and analytical abilities, while proofs must show logical reasoning—offering multiple approaches where possible—to deepen understanding. Mathematical results should be motivated by practical relevance, with explicit proofs  reinforcing reasoning and emphasizing the accurate articulation of arguments.\n\nFormatting Rules:\n1. Avoid including any additional headings or instructions—focus purely on the required content.\n2. When defining learning outcomes, use measurable action verbs like \"Solve,\" \"Analyze,\" \"Interpret,\" \"Construct,\" and \"Evaluate\" to clearly articulate what students will achieve.\n3. Each learning outcome should start with \"Students will be able to,\" followed by the specific intended outcome to ensure clarity and alignment with the objectives.\n4. Present all learning outcomes in a numbered, pointwise format for clarity and easy reference.\n5. Always use proper superscripts and subscripts in their readable format rather than using caret symbols or underscores.\nFor example:\nUse x² instead of x^2\nUse 10⁻³ instead of 10^-3\nUse m² instead of m^2\nUse v₁ instead of v_1\nUse T⁻¹ instead of T^-1\n**5.1 Generate all the mathematical equations, formulas only in readable format.\n\n6. Ensure that every mathematical equation, subscript, and superscript is placed correctly and displayed in a clear, easy-to-read format.\n7. Always adhere to the Indian metric system for measurements such as money, distance, and weight, using units like kilograms (kgs), metres, kilometres, and centimetres.\n\n Content Rules:\n1. Ensure the use of language that is both clear and concise.\n2. Ensure the consistent use of British English spellings in all written content.\n3. Ensure the use of correct grammar and punctuation consistently to maintain clarity and improve readability.\n4. All content and terminology must align with the specified [Grade] level, following the CBSE curriculum and NCERT textbook.\n5. All textbook concepts must be comprehensively covered through the learning outcomes.\n\nRules for generating learning outcomes:\n6. Generate all essential learning outcomes required for [Chapter Name] [Topic Name], strictly based on the given [Terms and Definitions].\n7. Adhere strictly to the order of [Terms and Definitions] provided when generating the learning outcomes.\n8. While creating Learning Outcomes (LOs) make sure that the LOs comprehensively and thoroughly cover all key aspects and details of the specific [Terms and Definitions].\n9. Identify similar terms and definitions, merge them and create a single, coherent learning\noutcome wherever applicable\n10. Avoid using examples in learning outcomes.\n11. Avoid adding new content that is not explicitly mentioned in the [Terms and Definitions].\n12. Make the objectives broader in scope while keeping the mathematical meaning intact. \n13. Avoid highly specific formulas or notation unless necessary. \n14. Make sure the LOs are academically generic.\n15. Each LO must address a distinct concept.\n16. The total number of learning outcomes should be limited to a maximum of 8–10.\n\nGenerate the output in this JSON format:\n[\n  {\n    \"learningOutcomes\": [\n      \"Students will be able to define Newton's First Law of Motion as the tendency of a body to remain at rest or in uniform motion unless acted upon by an external force.\",\n      \"Students will be able to differentiate between uniform and non-uniform motion using examples of objects moving at constant and varying speeds.\"\n    ]\n  }\n]",
